      "title": "[Boing Boing] Deep sleep could be the key to treating tinnitus, research suggests",
      "content_html": "<img src=\"https://i0.wp.com/boingboing.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/ear.jpg?fit=1200%2C800&quality=60&ssl=1\" style=\"width:100%;max-height:300px;object-fit:cover;\" />\n<a href=\"https://boingboing.net/2026/03/06/deep-sleep-could-be-the-key-to-treating-tinnitus-research-suggests.html\" rel=\"nofollow\" title=\"Deep sleep could be the key to treating tinnitus, research suggests\"><img alt=\"Human ear model (sasirin pamai/shutterstock.com)\" class=\"webfeedsFeaturedVisual wp-post-image\" height=\"800\" src=\"https://i0.wp.com/boingboing.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/ear.jpg?fit=1200%2C800&amp;quality=60&amp;ssl=1\" style=\"display: block; margin: auto; margin-bottom: 5px;\" width=\"1200\" /></a><p>Roughly one in seven people hears a persistent sound that doesn't exist — a ringing, buzzing, or hissing called tinnitus. It's the most widespread false sensory perception humans experience, and there's no cure. But new research from Oxford suggests sleep may hold the key to changing that. &#8212; <a class=\"read-more\" href=\"https://boingboing.net/2026/03/06/deep-sleep-could-be-the-key-to-treating-tinnitus-research-suggests.html\">Read the rest </a></p>\n<p>The post <a href=\"https://boingboing.net/2026/03/06/deep-sleep-could-be-the-key-to-treating-tinnitus-research-suggests.html\">Deep sleep could be the key to treating tinnitus, research suggests</a> appeared first on <a href=\"https://boingboing.net\">Boing Boing</a>.</p>",
